{
  "texts": [
    "This perpetuating cycle working via social media can lead to a positive feedback loop that exacerbates any initial polarization.",
    "Next, we extend a simplified version of the model of Acemoglu, Huttenlocher, Ozdaglar, and Siderius (2024) of online business models and digital ads to study our second channel for political polarization",
    "We let λ fraction of the users be sophisticated and 1 -λ fraction of the users be naïve.",
    "There is a state of the world θ ∈ {L, R} as before, and we suppose that users hold prior beliefs b i ∼ H. Sophisticated users have a correctly-specified subjective model of digital ads, which is that the signals s i contain no information about the underlying state θ.",
    "On the other hand, naïve agents believe that political ads contain information about θ, and that false positives are relatively rare."
  ]
}